s of origin. Attentive to both the economic context of industrial food production and the materiality of human-animal relations, this book highlights the fragile and contingent relational practices that constitute salmon aquaculture and the multiple ways of "becoming salmon" that emerge as a result.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aSalmon farmingxSocial aspects. 0aSalmon farming. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aanimal ethics.  aanimal husbandry.  aanimal rights.  aanimal studies.  aaquaculture.  aatlantic salmon.  abiologists.  afarmed salmon.  afish farming.  afish life.  afisheries.  afood scientists.  aglobal salmon trade.  ahuman animal relations.  aindustrial food production.  aindustrial husbandry.  ainternational food production.  amarine biologists.  amarine biology.  amarine domestication.  amarine life.  asalmon aquaculture.  asalmon farming.  asalmon farms.  asalmon fisheries.  asalmon trade.  asalmon.  aseafood.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z97831106211120 cprintz978052028056440uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052096183840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520961838423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520961838/original  a978-3-11-062111-2  University of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY